PRD EXAMPLES
EXAMPLE 1: GOOD PRD (GUIDED ONBOARDING)
See sections above for detailed example of a well-structured PRD covering all 10 sections. 
Why this works: 
Clear problem statement with evidence (interviews, analytics, support tickets) Personas grounded in research Solution description at right level of detail (not overly prescriptive) Success metrics with targets User stories with acceptance criteria Out of scope documented explicitly 
--- 
EXAMPLE 2: BAD PRD (FEATURE LIST)
Problem Statement: "Users want better onboarding." 
Solution: "Add onboarding." 
Requirements: "1. Onboarding flow Tooltips Help docs" 
Why this fails: 
No evidence (who wants this? why?) No personas (who is "users"?) No success metrics (how do we measure "better"?) No acceptance criteria (what does "onboarding flow" mean?) No strategic context (why now?) 
Fix with PRD workflow: 
Phase 2: Write problem statement with evidence from discovery interviews Phase 3: Define persona (Solo Entrepreneur Sam) Phase 6: Define success metrics (AR 40% → 60%) Phase 7: Break down "onboarding flow" into user stories with acceptance criteria 
